issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
We upgrade our repos from ort 1.6 (1.7 have also compiling issues with MSVC2017 #6912) to ort 1.8. Two compilation errors arise in
onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/reduction/reduction_ops

`
reduction_ops.h(215): error C2440: '<function-style-cast>': cannot convert from 'initializer list' to 'Eigen::Map<Eigen::Array<T,-1,1,,-1,1>,0,Eigen::Stride<0,0>>'
`

The changelog claims that a C++14 compliance is requested, we think that at least the last MSVC2017 is fully C++14 compliant, and MSVC2017 still the default target in ORT documentation
So is it possible to have a bug fix releases,  

**Urgency**
We are stuck in ort 1.6 and we want to move next month to lastest available version side by side with torch
And more than that the documentation claims MSVC2017 is the default compiler so we think we are not alone with this issue

clean build.

Thanks @snnn 
Something I discovered in the last few days if anyone is interested. Please correct me if I'm wrong:
In my C++ project that is supposed to execute the inference, I use VS2019 with V141 toolset. My concern was that if the C++ onnxruntime.dll cannot be built with V141 I might suffer from runtime problems due to the inconsistency of code generation between the different toolsets.
Since the dll has a C API which is wrapped by the C++ API, the entire resources management is done inside the dll, and the C++ API takes care of calling the C API, there should be should be no problem mixing a V141 toolset executable to a V142 dll. This assumption comes with a small asterisk - you'll have to statically link the dll with the MSVC runtime (add the flag --enable_msvc_static_runtime).

You don't have to do static link(though you can). The latest VS redist supports all of Visual Studio 2015, 2017, 2019, and 2022.  A single runtime for all of them.  The runtime should works well with V141 executables.

> you should use developer command promote for visual studio 2019 run the command line, and add the --cmake_generator "Visual Studio 16 2019"--use_openvino CPU_FP32 to the end of the .\build.bat , then you may be run success! 
I resolve the problem this way.

Hello,

I would like to reopen the issue, since using VS 2019 is not an option for me. I have looked into the code and it looks like the compiler is just unable to deal with lambdas properly.

Replacing the lambdas in FastReduceKRK and FastReduceRK inside reduction_ops.h with functors resolves the issues. I don't think that this would change the performance of these functions. 

If there is interest I can share the code.
